# Frontend architecture and API boundary

1. Keep frontend feature-based: domain screens in `features/`, shared shell/components in `components/`, transport and validators in `api/`.
2. The API layer is the canonical frontend boundary. Do not embed backend URLs or raw network calls directly into UI components.
3. Frontend should stay thin: prefer backend-first read-models over rebuilding heavy domain summaries from raw arrays in hooks/components.
4. Heavy tables or detail views should use server-side slices for filtering, sorting, totals, pagination, or lazy expansion instead of holding the whole dataset for local derive.
5. UI must render machine-readable statuses from the backend, not branch on user-facing labels.
6. Prefer explicit loading, success, error, and empty states before render. Do not rely on undefined data accidentally rendering.
7. `products -> product` should use one canonical workspace/snapshot read flow; do not reintroduce click-time materialize, warmup-gated reads, or parallel legacy fetch paths.
8. Product detail read-path must not be gated on `currentExport` hydration if `nmId` and the needed date range are already known.
9. `products` navigation stays list-first by default. Storage may preserve filters or UI state, but it must not auto-open detail unless there is an explicit deep link or deliberate user action.
10. Persisted dashboard state should stay deterministic and recoverable. Cache keys and request identity must remain canonical for the same resource.
11. User-facing text belongs in the shared UI copy layer, not as scattered hardcoded strings across the screen code.
